<DOC><DOCNO> AP881216-0281 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 1735EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f AM-Sandamp;LRescue     12-16 0229</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Sandamp;L Rescue,0237</SECOND><HEAD>FSLIC Aiding Ford in Michigan Sandamp;L Acquisitions</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Federal regulators said Friday they wereproviding $118.3 million in assistance to a subsidiary of Ford MotorCo. to rescue two Michigan savings institutions.   The two _ First Dearborn and Bloomfield Savings and LoanAssociation _ are being acquired by First Nationwide Bank, which isbased in San Francisco but is owned by Ford Motor Co. It has 400branches in 15 states and $23.6 billion in assets.   The Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp., which guaranteesSandamp;L deposits up to $100,000, is providing First Nationwide with a10-year promissory note with a face value of $174 million.   First Nationwide is paying a premium of $39 million and isturning over 80 percent of the tax benefits of the deal to theFSLIC, bank board spokesman Paul Olhkovsky said.   The two acquired institutions have 28 branches in the Detroitarea. They will open on Monday as branches of First Nationwide.   The rescue of First Dearborn and Bloomfield bring the total ofthrift rescues and closing for the year to 155, a post-Depressionrecord. Last year, the cases of 48 failed Sandamp;Ls were resolved.   Critics, including the congressional General Accounting Office,say the bank board should be given the money to close failedinstitutions and should end its strategy of keeping Sandamp;Ls alive withpromissory notes.</TEXT></DOC>